@node usage "USAGE"

Usage: TxtToHTML <inputfile> [outputfile] [options]

OPTIONS:
   -t, -title TITLE                  HTML Doc title
   -ctr, -centre                     Centre all text
   -iso2                             Convert AmigaPL -> ISO-8859-2
   -fs SIZE, -fsize SIZE             Font size (1-7) [Default is 3]
   -fc COLOUR, -fcolour COLOUR       Font colour
   -bgc COLOUR, -bgcolour COLOUR     BackGround colour
   -pre                              Preformated blocks @{"!!!" link pre}
   -nbsp                             Non-breaking space
   -pf                               Paragraph formatting
   -mkl, -makelinks                  Make links
   -lc COLOUR, -lcolour COLOUR       Link colour
   -alc COLOUR, -alcolour COLOUR     Actived link colour
   -vlc COLOUR, -vlcolour COLOUR     Visited link colour

Only the inputfile is required.

 inputfile      text file to convert
 outputfile     path to html file (converted inputfile)

@{apen 7}NOTE:  The program will accept both the American spelling of 
colour (color) and centre (center) OR the English, so fcolour or 
fcolor as well as center or centre are accepted.@{apen 1}

A list of font and backgrounds colours can be seen @{"here" link colours}.
You can also set colours by using the HEX code.
For example:

    FFFFFF  =  white   (for example: TxtToHTML in.txt -fcolor FFFFFF) 
    FF0000  =  red     (for example: TxtToHTML in.txt -bgcolor FF0000)  
    FF7F50  =  coral   (for example: TxtToHTML in.txt -fcolor FF7F50) 
    000000  =  black   (for example: TxtToHTML in.txt -bgcolor 000000) 

So using HEX code you can find the colour that you need.

@endnode
